Description: This project will upgrade the Borden Ave Pump Station. Footprint of the PS will be increased to ~ 2750 square feet. Convert dry well into wet well. Replace existing non-submersible pumps with submersible pumps while maintaining PS capacity of 3.9 MGD. Provide emergency portable diesel driven 4.5 MGD pump. Installation of new electrical, controls (SCADA), mechanical & HVAC systems. Provisions to support a future project to expand capacity of the PS from 3.9 MGD to 26 MGD. Upgrade resiliency per BWT guidelines. Line existing 14" Force Main

ProjectName: Croton Above Ground Structure And Landscaping
Description: The new Mosholu Golf Course Club House, together with fifty-five Driving Range Tee Boxes and ten-acres of re-landscaping comprise the phase IV and final of the vast DEP Croton Water Treatment Plant project, currently under construction in Van Cortlandt Park in the Bronx. Through a multifunctional design strategy the project reinstates the pre-existing golf program and facility, creates civic space for community use and ensures security for a multi-billion dollar public works facility.

Rehab Of Queens District 11/13 Sanitation Garage
Description: The Department of Sanitation of the City of New York (DSNY) is planning to rehabilitate Queens Districts 11 and 13 garage. The renovation serving both districts is to extend the useful life of the facility through rehabilitation of the building structure and systems. The renovation includes: Extensive structural work that includes the replacement of reinforced concrete slabs and stiffening of the existing steel frame, select replacement of building MEP systems, including BMS systems, architectural renovation of the entire building, study and implementation of deep energy conservation measures (DECMs), and site work which includes new landscape work and replacement of sidewalks and driveways. Rehabilitation is required to meet LEED Silver requirements.

Description: The Department of Sanitation of the City of New York (DSNY) is planning to rehabilitate Queens Districts 11 and 13 garage. The renovation serving both districts is to extend the useful life of the facility through rehabilitation of the building structure and systems. The renovation includes: Extensive structural work that includes the replacement of reinforced concrete slabs and stiffening of the existing steel frame, select replacement of building MEP systems, including BMS systems, architectural renovation of the entire building, study and implementation of deep energy conservation measures (DECMs), and site work which includes new landscape work and replacement of sidewalks and driveways. Rehabilitation is required to meet LEED Silver requirements.

Bronx Animal Care Center & Veterinary Clinic is a new 50,000 SF facility that will be housing admissions, adoptions, medical services, and boarding for approximately 70 dogs, 140 cats, 30 rabbits and 20 animals or other species. In addition to the animal housing, the Bronx Animal Care Center will include a wildlife area to rehabilitate wild birds, academic partnership for youth, and enhanced senior services. Site work will include yards to facilitate dog adoptions, covered exercise runs, courtyards, and parking for staff, visitors, and shelter vehicles, as well as site lighting and low maintenance planting throughout. The building and associated landscape are to achieve LEED Gold standards.

Site work will include yards to facilitate dog adoptions, covered exercise runs, courtyards, and parking for staff, visitors, and center vehicles, as well as site lighting and low maintenance planting throughout. The building and associated landscape are to achieve LEED Silver standards or higher.

ProjectName: Queens Botanical Garden Educ Bldg Renovation

Design and construction of a new 14,500 SF building to provide year-round programming and educational spaces to serve students, children, community gardeners, and others.  The New Education Building will add six new teaching spaces, including four classrooms, a teaching kitchen and a teaching greenhouse where educators will be able to grow and maintain plants for educational purposes. Ideally, the four regular classrooms will be able to opened up into one large space to accommodate larger training programs.

Roof andThe project for which services are required is the rehabilitation of the Brooklyn Districts 17 and 18 Sanitation Garage, located at 10502 Avenue D, Brooklyn, NY 11236. Block: 8136/Lot: 1. The 159,500 total gross square foot, masonry-veneered and steel framed facility is located in eastern Brooklyn at the intersection of the Avenue D and the 105th St. This building was completed in 1991 and was last renovated in 1998.  The main objective of this project is to extend the useful life of this facility through rehabilitation of the building Roofing, and HVAC systems and adding a Solar Ready Systems. The rehabilitation shall include the following: replacement of the roof (membrane, select areas of decking, select roof drains and domes, select skylights and coordination for future solar panel locations), structural work (stiffening of the existing structural steel frame, supports for new HVAC equipment and solar panels and select parapet replacement), select replacement of building systems (electrical, fire protection and HVAC (including BMS)), building expansion joints and architectural renovation of the entire building to repair water damage.  The funding for solar program provided by DCAS.
